1290","1226–1300":"1226–1300","1266–Female":"1266–Overleden","1271–Female":"1271–Overleden","–1296":"–1296","1238–Male":"1238–Overleden","1180–1210":"1180–1210","1296":"1296","1271":"1271","1180":"1180","1290":"1290","1238":"1238","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1266":"1266","1210":"1210","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Harswell, Yorkshire, England":"Harswell, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1200–1271":"1200–1271","1245–1290":"1245–1290","1226–1300":"1226–1300","1266–Female":"1266–Deceased","1271–Female":"1271–Deceased","–1296":"–1296","1238–Male":"1238–Deceased","1180–1210":"1180–1210","1296":"1296","1271":"1271","1180":"1180","1290":"1290","1238":"1238","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1266":"1266","1210":"1210","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Harswell, Yorkshire, England":"Harswell, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Salvain","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Emile, Fernand, Jacques, Michel, Pierre, Andre, Armand, Benoit, Fernande, Francois, Gardy, Germain.","French and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the French personal name <i>Sylvain</i>, from Latin <i>Silvanus</i> (a derivative of <i>silva</i> ‘forest, wood’), bestowed in honor of various minor early Christian saints. This surname is most common in Haiti.","History: Pierre Sylvain <i>dit</i> Larosée from Saintes in Charente-Maritime, France, married Jeanne Périllard in Montreal, QC, in 1720. — In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Pierre Veau <i>dit</i> Sylvain (a son of Sylvain Veau from Valençay in Indre, France), who married Catherine Racine in Beaupré, QC, in 1722."],"variants":[{"name":"Sylvan","meanings":["Swedish: ornamental name derived from the Latin adjective <i>silvanus</i> ‘pertaining to a wood or forest’ (a derivative of <i>silva</i> ‘forest, wood’), used as a translation of the Swedish name element <i>skog</i> ‘forest’.","West Indian (Trinidad and Tobago, Grenada): from the personal name <i>Sylvan</i>, from Latin <i>Silvanus</i> (see   Sylvain  )."]},{"name":"Salvant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Cyrille, Lucien, Michel.","French: variant of <b>Sauvant</b>, from an old vernacular form of the personal name   Sylvain  ."]}]},{"name":"Gerard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy, strong’. In the later Middle Ages this was a more common name than   Gerald  , with which it was sometimes confused. Nowadays it is less common, surviving mainly among Roman Catholics, in honour of the many saints of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Gerard  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Jerrard","meanings":["Rare variant spelling of   Gerard  , probably influenced by the form of the modern surname, if not a transferred use."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":59,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Gerard Salvain I was born in 1200, in Harswell, Yorkshire, England as the son of William Salvain II. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Joan Baseville. He died in 1271, in his hometown, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1200–1271":"1200–1271","1245–1290":"1245–1290","1226–1300":"1226–1300","1266–Female":"1266–Surnud","1271–Female":"1271–Surnud","–1296":"–1296","1238–Male":"1238–Surnud","1180–1210":"1180–1210","1296":"1296","1271":"1271","1180":"1180","1290":"1290","1238":"1238","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1266":"1266","1210":"1210","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Harswell, Yorkshire, England":"Harswell, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1200–1271":"1200–1271","1245–1290":"1245–1290","1226–1300":"1226–1300","1266–Female":"1266–Kuollut","1271–Female":"1271–Kuollut","–1296":"–1296","1238–Male":"1238–Kuollut","1180–1210":"1180–1210","1296":"1296","1271":"1271","1180":"1180","1290":"1290","1238":"1238","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1300":"1300","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","1266":"1266","1210":"1210","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Harswell, Yorkshire, England":"Harswell, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1200–1271":"1200–1271","1245–1290":"1245–1290","1226–1300":"1226–1300","1266–Female":"1266–Décédée","1271–Female":"1271–Décédée","–1296":"–1296","1238–Male":"1238–Décédé","118